record_data.record_plain_text: Dow Intrastate Gas, LLC STATEMENT PURSUANT TO SECTION 284.123(e) This statement describes how Dow Intrastate Gas, LLC ("Transporter"), an intrastate pipeline, will engage in new transportation arrangements conducted under Section 311(a)(2) of The Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978 ("NGPA") for any eligible shipper. Transporter shall be satisfied of Shipper's financial position, using reasonable standards of creditworthiness consistently applied, pursuant to Paragraph 22 below. Transporter shall also be satisfied, in its sole opinion, that the service will be on behalf of an interstate pipeline or a local distribution company served by an interstate pipeline, and may require appropriate assurance in writing to that effect. It shall be the policy of Transporter to render such transportation service subject to available capacity on an interruptible basis only, and pursuant to written contracts containing terms and conditions generally acceptable to Transporter as set forth herein, executed after consideration of its existing commitments, pipeline design capacity and available pipeline capacity, points of receipt and points of delivery, and reserves the right to vary from such general terms provided that any such variations are not materially detrimental to any other shipper similarly situated. 1 Definitions: The terms 1.1 "day" shall mean a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive hours beginning and ending at 9:00 a.m., Central Time ("CT"); 1.2 "month" shall mean a period of one calendar month commencing at 9:00 a.m. CT on the first day of such month; 1.3 "year" shall mean a period of three-hundred sixty-five (365) consecutive days commencing and ending at 9:00 a.m. CT, provided that any year which contains that date of February 29 shall consist of three-hundred sixty-six (366) days; 1.4 "cubic foot of gas" shall mean the amount of gas contained in one cubit foot of space at a pressure of 15.025 pounds per square inch absolute ("psia") and at a temperature of sixty (60) degrees Fahrenheit; 1.5 "MCF" shall mean one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of gas; 1.6 "Btu" shall mean British thermal unit; 1.7 "MMBtu" shall mean one million (1,000,000) British thermal units; 1.8 "Gas" or "natural gas" shall mean any mixture of hydrocarbons or of hydrocarbons and non-combustible gas, in a gaseous state, consisting essentially of methane; and 1.9 "Shipper" shall mean the party for whom gas is transported, or requested to be transported, on Transporter's system. 2 Governmental regulation. The transportation arrangement will be subject to all valid existing and future laws, orders, rules, regulations or proclamations of duly constituted authorities having jurisdiction or control over the parties thereto or the subject matter thereof including, without limitation, the provisions of Subpart C of Part 284 of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission's ("FERC") regulations (18 CFR Section 284.121 et. seq.) implementing Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA. In any such governmental authority shall take any action which is, with respect to or as a result of the transportation agreement, designed to subject or otherwise subjects either party or any of its pipeline or related facilities to any greater or different regulations or jurisdiction than that existing on the date of the contract (or thereafter as such regulation or jurisdiction may have changed and been accepted by such party), then upon written notice to the other, the party so affected may cancel and terminate the transportation arrangement effective one (1) day prior to the effective date of such governmental action without further obligation to the other party except, in the case of Shipper, to make payment for services rendered and, in the case of either Transporter or Shipper, to correct any gas imbalance existing on the date of such termination. 3 Receipt and Delivery of Transportation Gas. Subject to Transporter's own operating requirements, the availability of excess capacity in its existing compression and pipeline facilities not required for its own use from time to time, the availability of capacity sufficient to provide the service without detriment or disadvantage to all of its intrastate customers, and the availability of capacity not necessary to serve existing customers with contracts for service provided under Section 311 of the NGPA, service will be provided on a fully interruptible basis only, and involve the receipt for Shipper's account at a mutually agreeable point to points of receipt (Transporter Receipt Point) of certain designated quantities of natural gas (not less than 1,000 MCF per day) and the redelivery to Shipper or its designee at a mutually agreeable point or points of delivery (Transporter Delivery Point) of quantities equivalent on a heating value basis to the aggregate MCF's received for the account of Shipper at the Transporter Receipt Point reduced by the Btu's, if any, which are required for compressor fuel in the rendition of the service. 4 Term. Service will be provided for a term of up to two (2) years from the date of initial deliveries, and thereafter may remain in force and effect unless terminated by either party upon termination given to the other party; provided, however, Transporter shall have the right to terminate or suspend service immediately upon prior written notice of such termination or suspension given to Shipper in the event (i) Transporter, on a non-discriminatory basis, shall also concurrently terminate or suspend, as the case may be, all of its NGPA Section 311 transportation service of the type provided for under the transportation arrangement which, in the absence of such termination or suspension, would in Transporter's sole discretion cause Transporter to be subject to the non-discriminatory access provisions contained in Part 284 of the FERC's regulations, or (ii) deliveries of gas for transportation under the transportation agreement, once commenced, have ceased for any period of one hundred eighty (180) consecutive days or more and not resumed. Shipper shall immediately notify transporter, by telegram or other mutually acceptable method, of the occurrence of initial deliveries, which shall be by mutual agreement of the parties. 5 Determination and Balancing of Deliveries. Dispatchers of Transporter and Shipper or its designee will mutually agree upon the quantities to be scheduled for transportation each day. It shall be the intention of Transporter that daily deliveries to Shipper or its designee at the Transporter Delivery Point will be equal on a heating value basis to daily receipts by Transporter for Shipper's account at the Transporter Receipt Point less compressor fuel, if any. However, due to variations in operating conditions, daily and monthly deliveries by transporter may be greater or less than the corresponding receipts of gas by Transporter. Any such excess or deficiency will be adjusted or corrected in gas as soon as operating conditions reasonable permit. 6 Delivery Pressure, Assumed Atmospheric Pressure. Gas delivered for transportation at the Transporter Receipt Point shall be delivered at a pressure sufficient to enter Transporter's pipeline facilities at such point, but in no event in excess of Transporter's maximum allowable operating pressure at such point and at an assumed atmospheric pressure of 14.73 psia. Transporter shall not be required to change its operating conditions or install facilities, including compression, to enable the receipt or delivery of Shipper's gas. 7 Measurement. Quantities delivered under the transportation arrangement at the applicable Transporter Receipt and Delivery Points will be determined by the party responsible for measurement at each such point at a temperature of 60 degrees Fahrenheit, at a pressure of 15.025 psia and on the basis of AGA Gas measurement Committee Report No. 3, including any amendments or revisions thereof. The applicable Btu content of the gas so delivered will be determined on a gross, saturated basis, and then corrected to actual gas conditions as delivered, using mutually agreeable methods. 8 Measurement Equipment. Unless otherwise agreed to by the parties, Transporter will install, if necessary, operate and maintain such measuring and related facilities as are necessary for the measurement, in MMBtu's and MCF's of gas delivered at the Transporter Receipt Point and at the Transporter Delivery Point; provided, however, Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for any and all costs incurred by transporter in connection with the installation of such facilities. 9 Quality. Gas received and delivered under the transportation arrangement shall be merchantable natural gas and shall contain (i) not more than two-tenth (0.2) of one percent (1%) by volume of oxygen, (ii) not more than one-quarter (1/4) grain hydrogen sulfide per one hundred cubic feet, (iii) not more than ten (10) grains of total sulphur per one hundred (100) cubic feet, (iv) not more than four percent (4%) by volume of combined carbon dioxide and nitrogen, nor more than three percent (3%) by volume of carbon dioxide, (v) not more than seven (7) pounds of water vapor per one million (1,000,000) cubic feet, (vi) an average heating content of not less than nine hundred fifty (950) Btu's nor more than eleven hundred fifty (1,150) Btu's per cubic foot, (vii) shall not contain more than 0.2 gallons per MCF of natural gasoline and (viii) shall not have a temperature of less than 40 degrees Fahrenheit nor more than 120 degrees Fahrenheit (120 F). 10 Transportation Fee. The transportation fee will not exceed that maximum fair and equitable rate as determined in accordance with the FERC's regulations, or an adjustment therefrom, or as established by any other governmental authority having jurisdiction. To the extent that it is legally permissible, Transporter shall in addition have the right to charge Shipper; 10.1 for the costs of any facilities installed by Transporter to receive or deliver natural gas for the account of Shipper; 10.2 for any and all fees required in connection with Shipper's Transportation Agreement that Transporter is obligated to pay to The Commission or any other governmental authority having jurisdiction; 10.3 for Shipper's pro rata share of the cost of compressor fuel used by Transporter on any day. 11 Capacity Allocations. Subject to Transporter's needs and the availability of capacity, service under Section 311 of the Natural Gas Policy Act by Transporter will be made available to all qualified Shippers. Capacity of Transporter's system will be allocated on a first come, first served basis, with a Shipper's place in the allocation queue determined at the time a valid request for transportation is received in the form described in Paragraph 12 herein. 12 Requests for Transportation. Transporter will accept as valid only those requests which, in Transporter's sole judgment, are sufficiently specific with respect to the following information, all of which must be provided as set forth below: 12.1 Gas quantities for which transportation service is requested, stated in both MCF and MMBtu per day; 12.2 Transporter Receipt Points: 12.2.1 Point(s) of entry into Transporter's system; 12.2.2 Name of entity delivering into Transporter's system; 12.3 Transporter Delivery Points: 12.3.1 Point(s) of delivery by Transporter; 12.3.2 Entity receiving gas downstream of Transporter; 12.4 Term of Proposed Service: 12.4.1 Date service requested to commence; 12.4.2 Date service requested to terminate; 12.5 A certification that the Shipper has a current contractual right to acquire the gas to be delivered to Transporter for transportation and will enter into those arrangements necessary to assure all upstream and downstream transportation will be in place prior to the execution of a transportation service agreement; 12.6 The name, address, title and telephone number of the officer of Shipper who will execute the service agreement with Transporter and to whom the original(s) of that agreement should be sent; 12.7 No request will be considered valid if received by Transporter more than thirty (30) days in advance of when service is requested to commence. Requests that cannot be fulfilled because of capacity constraints on Transporter's system will be valid for thirty (30) days, after which they will be considered to be null and void unless Shipper, within that thirty day period, notifies Transporter that Shipper is renewing its request. Renewal requests will not be subject to any additional deposit. 12.8 When Transporter has determined that there is sufficient capacity available to offer transportation service to a Shipper under a valid request for transportation, Transporter will transmit to Shipper a Gas Transportation Agreement consistent with the terms and conditions set forth herein. If Shipper does not execute said agreement and place it in the U.S. Mail properly addressed to Transporter within fifteen (15) days of receipt, Shipper will lose its place in the capacity-allocation queue. 12.9 Any reimbursement due Transporter by Shipper pursuant to this section shall be due and payable to Transporter within ten (10) days of receipt of Shipper of Transporter's invoice(s) for same. 13 Billing and Payment. On or before the tenth (10th) day of each month, Transporter will submit to Shipper a statement setting forth under the transportation arrangement during the immediately proceeding month, and the amount payable to Transporter therefor. Shipper shall pay Transporter the full amount according to such statement, at Transporter's designated address for payment, on or before the twentieth (20th) day of each month, such payment being considered timely if it is postmarked on or before the date due. If presentation of such statement is delayed beyond the tenth (10th) day of the month, then the time of payment thereof shall be extended for the period of delay. Should Shipper fail to pay the full amount of any such bill for gas delivered, when such amount is due, interest shall accrue on the unpaid portion thereof at a varying rate per annum equal to the prime rate from time to time in effect from the date of the contract and charged by Citibank NA, Houston, Texas, to its largest and most creditworthy commercial borrowers on nine-day (90) commercial loans plus two percent (2%) (but in no event greater than the maximum rate of interest permitted by law) with adjustments in such rate to be made on the same day as any change in such prime rate, for any period during which the same shall be overdue, such interest to be paid when the amount past due is paid. Transporter will have the right to discontinue service under the transportation arrangement if any amount which is owed to it for transportation services provided thereunder remains unpaid for ten (10) days following the due date thereof. 14 Possession of Gas, Title and Responsibility. As between Transporter and Shipper, Transporter will be deemed to be in control and possession of the gas after its delivery to Transporter at the Transporter Receipt Point and prior to its delivery to Shipper or its designee at the Transporter Delivery Point. The party in control and possession of the gas will be responsible for and shall indemnify the other party with respect to any losses, injuries, claims, liabilities or damages caused thereby and occurring while the gas is in its possession. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Shipper shall at all times have title to all gas transported under the transportation arrangement. 15 Indemnification. Each party will agree that with respect to the gas delivered or redelivered by it under the transportation arrangement, it will indemnify and save the other party harmless from and against any and all suits, actions, causes of actions, claims and demands arising from or out of any adverse claims by third parties claiming ownership of or an interest in the gas so delivered or redelivered. 16 Force Majeure. In the event of either Shipper or Transporter being rendered unable by force majeure to itself or a necessary third party to wholly or in part carry out its obligations under the transportation arrangement, the obligations of the party affected by such force majeure, other than the obligation to make payment of amounts due under the transportation arrangement, shall be suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused but for no longer period, and such cause shall, so far as possible, be remedied with all reasonable dispatch. The term "Force Majeure" shall mean acts and events not within the control of the party claiming suspension. 17 Law Applicable. The contract covering the transportation arrangements shall be governed by the laws of the State of Louisiana. 18 Successors and Assign. The contract covering the transportation arrangement shall be binding upon and insure to the benefit of the successors, assigns and legal representatives of the parties; provided, however, neither party thereto shall assign the contract, or any portion thereof, or any of its rights and obligations thereunder without first obtaining the prior written consent of the other party; and, provided further, either party shall have the right to pledge or mortgage its respective rights under the contract for security of its indebtedness without the prior written consent of the other party. 19 Conditions Precedent. In the event that on or before ninety (90) days subsequent to the date of the contract covering the transportation arrangement deliveries of gas for transportation thereunder have not commenced, then in such event and thereafter, until such deliveries are tendered and accepted, either party may cancel the contract tendered and accepted by giving written notice of such written cancellation to the other party. Transporter shall be under no obligation to commence service under the transportation arrangement unless and until (i) all facilities, of whatever nature, as are required to permit the receipt, measurement, transportation and delivery of natural gas thereunder have been installed and are in operating condition, and (ii) Shipper has arranged for the delivery and receipt by any necessary third party transporter of volumes to be transported and delivered thereunder by Transporter. 20 Representation and Warranties. Shipper will represent and warrant that it (A)(i) is an "intrastate pipeline" within the meaning of Sections 2(15) and 311 of the NGPA and Subpart C of Part 284 of the FERC's regulations, or (ii) is the "local distribution company served by an interstate pipeline(s)" within the meaning of Section 2(17) and 311 of the NGPA and Subpart C of Part 284 of the FERC's regulations, or (iii) is authorized by an interstate pipeline or local distribution company to arrange transportation pursuant to Section 311 of NGPA on behalf of such interstate pipeline or local distribution company, and (B) has arranged for the delivery and receipt by any necessary third party transporter of volumes to be transported and delivered by Transporter under the transportation arrangement. 21 Notices. Any notice, request, demand, statement, bill or payment provided for under the transportation arrangement or any notice which a party may desire to give to the other, shall be in writing and shall be considered as duly delivered when mailed to the other party at the address set forth in the transportation agreement in a manner similar to that set forth below: If to Shipper: FOR BILLING AND STATEMENTS: _______________________________ _______________________________ _______________________________ _______________________________ NOTICES & OPERATIONAL MATTERS: _______________________________ _______________________________ _______________________________ _______________________________ If to Transporter: FOR REMITTANCE _______________________________ _______________________________ _______________________________ _______________________________ FOR NOTICES & OPERATIONAL MATTERS: _______________________________ _______________________________ _______________________________ _______________________________ FOR ACCOUNTING MATTERS: _______________________________ _______________________________ _______________________________ _______________________________ or at such other address as either party may designate in writing. Routine communications shall be considered as duly delivered as of the postmark date when mailed by ordinary mail. Operating communications by telephone or other mutually agreeable means shall be considered as duly delivered without subsequent written confirmation unless written confirmation is requested by either party. 22 Creditworthiness. 22.1 Transporter shall not be required to perform or continue to perform service on behalf of any Shipper (i) that has applied for bankruptcy under any chapter of the Bankruptcy Code, (ii) that fails to make prompt and full payment to Transporter when due for services rendered by Transporter, or (iii) for which Transporter has reasonable grounds for insecurity as to Shipper's performance of its obligations under any transaction governed hereby. If any event set forth in (i), (ii) or (iii) shall occur, in addition to any other rights or remedies available to Transporter, it may in writing demand adequate assurance of due performance and until it receives such assurance, may suspend any performance for which it has not already been paid. 22.2 Adequate assurance of performance of the type described in Paragraph 22.1 above shall include (i) posting of a letter of credit in form and from a financial institution acceptable to Transporter in an amount equal to three months of transportation charges; (ii) cash prepayment in an amount equal to three months of transportation charges; or (iii) delivery of other forms of security acceptable to the Transporter in an amount equal to three months of demand charges. Shipper's failure to deliver adequate assurance properly demanded within two business days of receiving Transporter's demand therefore shall constitute a breach of the applicable transportation transaction, entitling Transporter to (i) terminate any or all transportation transactions with Shipper, (ii) liquidate Gas balances in Transporter's possession and applying the resulting funds to the payment of all amounts owed and that become owed for services under any transportation transactions governed by this statement of operating conditions, and (iii) seek all other remedies available for breach for all applicable transportation transactions.
